text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Discrimination in Tests and Language Learning Tools%0a%0a:Author: rajeev_g%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aI discuss linguistic discrimination in tests for English language proficiency as well as in language learning apps for English.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aPronunciations of English words vary significantly across different dialects across the US and across the world. However, far too often, language tests like the IELTS and language learning frameworks like Duolingo require one correct pronunciation. This pronunciation tends to be associated with prestige dialects, and results in those who speak different dialects being assessed poorly or told to speak in another way.%0a%0aIELTS and DuoLingo have provided a grant to Okim Kang, who is studying how to make tests and learning frameworks more fair. She argues that "non-native speakers of English or speakers with accents cannot be marginalized just because they have an accent." [1]%0a%0aThe specific linguistic features that are at the root of this discrimination are not mentioned, but the article opens by mentioning the pronunciation of the word "pecan." Even with American dialects, there are four distinct pronunciations: [piːˈkaːn], [pɪˈkaːn], [ˈpɪːkæn], and [ˈpiːkaːn].%0a%0aOn a personal note, I know that my father, who has actually published an (Indian) English book, was faulted on his speaking exam when applying to become a doctor in the US for putting the "wrong" stress on words like "inundated." Not only is the prescriptive nature of this test troubling, it seems curious why it would be relevant to his ability to practice medicine in any case.%0a%0a[1] https://news.nau.edu/kang-english-accents/#.YIzOS6lKgTU%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-165338-944900#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Personal experience of taking the TOEFL test %0a-> - Mingkang_L%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAs a non-native speaker of English, TOEFL was part of our college application process, and the speaking section of the TOEFL test was based on Standard American English. Although Educational Testing Service (ETS) claims that accent is not a part of the rubric, but the feedback from many of my peers suggested the contrary—having a perfect Standard American accent usually results in a higher score. In the name of “standardized tests,” ETS actually prescribes what “proper English” should be for non-native speakers of English. %0aI had a math professor a few semester ago who also received implicit linguistic discrimination. She put a lot of time and effort into her lectures, and the lecture notes are very clear and succinct compared to the textbook. However, she wasn’t liked by many students because of her accent, which was indeed quite hard to understand at first but everyone should have no problem adapting to after just a few lectures. Unfortunately%0a, I still see some online discussions about the professor’s accent being “a bit hilarious,” and students sometimes parody her accent by changing the spelling of some certain words. It seems that linguistics discrimination really isn’t far from us, so this definitely is something that we need to be more aware of.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-165338-944900#%0a#foxbegin 210509-022546-773670#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Linguistic Discrimination by Examiners %0a-> - BrandonW%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aExaminers have sometimes inaccurately assess children from linguistic backgrounds other than Standard American English. One result that has occurred is that minorities are overrepresented in special education programs. A reason that inaccurate assessments occur is that an examiner may not be fully familiar with a person's cultural/linguistic background. An example is that in African American English, the sentence "he walks to school" is actually said as "he walk to school" as the third person "-s" is deleted. An examiner may believe that this is evidence of language disorder when in reality it is a part of the person's dialect. Another reason is that tests are written in Standard American English instead of in a speaker's linguistic background, so scores on the test maybe lower than what they should be.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-022546-773670#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210509-022653-304750#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-08.05.2021 - 19:26-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210509-022653-304750 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!BrandonW%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Source for my expansion (BrandonW)'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aHere is my source: https://www.leadersproject.org/2013/03/01/how-does-linguistic-bias-affect-language-evaluations/ %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-022653-304750#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
