diff:1620527146:1620320017:=64,72d63%0a%3c #foxbegin 210509-022546-773670#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Linguistic Discrimination by Examiners %0a%3c -> - BrandonW%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Examiners have sometimes inaccurately assess children from linguistic backgrounds other than Standard American English. One result that has occurred is that minorities are overrepresented in special education programs. A reason that inaccurate assessments occur is that an examiner may not be fully familiar with a person's cultural/linguistic background. An example is that in African American English, the sentence "he walks to school" is actually said as "he walk to school" as the third person "-s" is deleted. An examiner may believe that this is evidence of language disorder when in reality it is a part of the person's dialect. Another reason is that tests are written in Standard American English instead of in a speaker's linguistic background, so scores on the test maybe lower than what they should be.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210509-022546-773670#%0a
