diff:1620320017:1619846803:=53,63c53%0a%3c #foxbegin 210506-165338-944900#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Personal experience of taking the TOEFL test %0a%3c -> - Mingkang_L%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c As a non-native speaker of English, TOEFL was part of our college application process, and the speaking section of the TOEFL test was based on Standard American English. Although Educational Testing Service (ETS) claims that accent is not a part of the rubric, but the feedback from many of my peers suggested the contrary—having a perfect Standard American accent usually results in a higher score. In the name of “standardized tests,” ETS actually prescribes what “proper English” should be for non-native speakers of English. %0a%3c I had a math professor a few semester ago who also received implicit linguistic discrimination. She put a lot of time and effort into her lectures, and the lecture notes are very clear and succinct compared to the textbook. However, she wasn’t liked by many students because of her accent, which was indeed quite hard to understand at first but everyone should have no problem adapting to after just a few lectures. Unfortunately%0a%3c , I still see some online discussions about the professor’s accent being “a bit hilarious,” and students sometimes parody her accent by changing the spelling of some certain words. It seems that linguistics discrimination really isn’t far from us, so this definitely is something that we need to be more aware of.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210506-165338-944900#%0a---%0a> %0a
